Author: MarcelH#6646
Content: Hello, I am new here. Can someone help me to understand following question in the first assignment. "Suppose that the names in a phone book with n names are not alphabetized but randomly ordered instead. Using "big-oh" notation, what's an upper bound on the running time of searching that phone book for some name? Why?" I do not ask for the answer, just a brief explanation what is meant with"big-oh" notation and how does it relate to search time for a certain name in the phone book. Thanks in advance.

Author: rj2808#5718
Content: Hi @MarcelH. The "big-oh" notation is a mathematical function used in computer science to represent the performance of an algorithm. For example, and in the context of searching the phonebook, if your algorithm is programmed to search every page for a specific name, then you would represent the performance of this algorithm as O(n). If, like in the lecture, your algorithm cut the phonebook in half, then its performance would be O(log n). I hope this makes sense, but if it did not, here are a few resources that I found online : https://rob-bell.net/2009/06/a-beginners-guide-to-big-o-notation/, https://www.freecodecamp.org/news/big-o-notation-simply-explained-with-illustrations-and-video-87d5a71c0174/

Author: MarcelH#6646
Content: Hi @rj2808 thank you for this useful explanation.
